[2] Australia (Western Australia): travel related, comment
Date: Tue 17 Apr 2018
From: Gary Dowse <Gary.Dowse@health.wa.gov.au> [edited]


Western Australia has had 2 cases of measles confirmed in recent days in infants who travelled on separate but connecting Malindo Air flights, as detailed below. The index case was almost certainly an adult who was infected in India and was experiencing prodromal symptoms during both these flights, and was diagnosed with measles (genotype D8), following arrival in Perth. Onset of illness in the 2 infants, who were too young to have been vaccinated, occurred 8 and 9 days, respectively, following the flights.

The flights were:
1. Malindo Air flight OD 272, departing Amritsar, India on 29 Mar 2018 at 22:30, and arriving in Kuala Lumpur [Malaysia] on 30 Mar 2018 around 07:00.
2. Malindo Air flight OD 151, departing Kuala Lumpur [Malaysia] on 30 Mar 2018 around 08:25, and arriving in Perth (Western Australia) on 30 Mar 2018 around 14:10.

Precise seating information was not available for any of the 3 cases, but it seems that the secondary cases were likely to have been seated in the same general area of the cabin as was the infectious case on each of the flights in common.

It is possible that there could have been transmission on either of these flights to nationals of other countries, and this information may be of value in determining the source of infection.

--
Dr Gary Dowse
Medical Epidemiologist
Communicable Disease Control Directorate
Department of Health
Western Australia
<Gary.Dowse@health.wa.gov.au>

[ProMED thanks Dr Dowse for submitting this information on flight related measles cases. - Mod.LK

