[3] New Zealand (Waikato): travel related
Date: Wed 18 April 2018 14:53 NZST
Source: Voxy [edited]
http://www.voxy.co.nz/health/5/308733


People at Hamilton [Waikato] branches of Bunnings, New World, and PAK'nSAVE are being urged to check their measles immunity status after a person with the viral illness was in the stores.

The Waikato DHB [District Health Board] Public Health team has confirmed a case of measles in a person who caught the disease overseas before returning to New Zealand. This is unrelated to the recent cases in the South Island.

Medical Officer of Health Dr Richard Vipond said measles is a highly infectious illness and people who share the same air as someone while they were infectious may be at risk of developing the disease if they are not already immune.

People who visited the stores listed in the URL above during the appropriate time periods are recommended to check their immune status with their General Practice.

People most at risk of contracting the disease are those who have not had the measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine or who have had just one dose of the vaccine. Anyone born before 1969 is likely to be immune from the disease without having had the vaccine.

Dr Vipond said "Measles is a serious illness, many measles cases require hospital treatment. Measles is infectious for several days before the characteristic rash appears and is very easily transmitted from one person to another through the air."

He said anyone who visited the stores at those times and feels they may be unwell should telephone their doctor or call Healthline on 0800 611-116 for advice. People should not go directly to a doctor's office or to a hospital emergency department, but call first because measles is highly infectious and people with measles can infect others in the waiting room.

"The only way to protect from measles and the best way to avoid its complications is to be fully vaccinated. People who visited the above stores should check that they have had two MMR vaccines. Catch up vaccinations are free, so we encourage everyone to check their immunisation status and if they are not immune to be vaccinated," said Dr Vipond.

How to protect you and your family against measles:
Make sure you and your children are fully immunised. It's the best way to provide protection against a number of diseases and complications. Check your immunisation status with your GP.

Measles can't be treated once you get it, so the only way to prevent the disease is through free immunisation.

